segments.text: and i'll go ahead and well before i go to your children i'd like to ask a little bit more about these lands you you say that that after a while the people who were working them just never
And your aunts and uncles then began to try to get them back?
My aunt, ,, tried to get rid of us.
Well, I think she took too long.
They probably thought, well, we'll do it Sunday.
But they got to a point that time passed, and they never did anything about it until it was too late.
Like, for instance, the people that took over the lands got old, and their sons took over.
So some of these people had already died, the first people that kept them.
So these new people, they wouldn't recognize anybody, because they'd probably say, well, we've been here so long, and 90% is the precision of the law, so it's ours.
They probably got papers on it too, you know.
That's why she never could do anything about it.
But I think they waited too long to do anything about it.
So they didn't really start trying to do anything until about 1931, which is when these papers were.
Yes, that's when my father was going to take charge of it.
And try to get the right back for him.
And then from then on, several years passed when he tried it again, when Santa Clarita tried it, and it was already too late.
Well, you can see in this part, one of the, one, Simon Parra, was, was saying that it would be all right for him.
He was one of the, one that stayed with the land.
He was taking care of it.
No, he was a neighbor of my father or something.
He had the same, was he a cousin?
And so this document says, in effect, could you just sort of read that in English?
Say more or less what it says in English.

was going to send my aunts what they can and he was going to take care of the ranches and tell them once in a while that he was going to send money and he was going to pay the Texas over there and he was in charge.
That's why this document was made so they agreed for him to stay over there so he could send something.
But as the year passed by, they forgot all about it and they knew something about anything.
And that's why this was the last thing they did.
So in 1931, he actually, this man, Simon Bada, actually agreed that he was renting and that he would send them some money.
So he accepted their ownership in that year.
But then nothing ever came up.
Well, my aunt cried hard afterwards, too.
Here, you can see a map with more... Is that the sketch?
Something about kilometers and the ranches of Fernando Leal.
The ones that stayed on those parts of the ranches.
Alvarez, Ornones, Juarez, Miguel Barra, Fernando Zambrano.
So these are people who stayed on the land.
And eventually, they and their heirs took it over.
Now, did they all stay in Mexico?
Or did any of them come to the States?
I think they all stayed over there in Mexico.
I believe none of those, I don't think any of those people actually lived, no one lived very long, or after your Tia Leta was trying to get the land back, none of them were living.
No, I think they were all.
Yeah, only their sons, their heirs were.
And their heirs would never get them up.
She had a lot of things, a lot of people, and I think they're all
Now they even tried to say that they were the owners of the land, see?
Because Estos Seores Se Basan, they were talking about the titulos, que they already expired from my aunt, so she didn't have contra la ley.
They have a law in Mexico, I don't understand very clearly, but I think that if a piece of land is abandoned,
And after so many years, nobody lays claim to them.
That person, any person, can go and they call it denunciar.
I don't know what that word would mean in English.
And they in turn, if it's publicized in papers or someone, if nobody turns up,
Claiming the land, now they could give title to it.
And that it would be a clear title.
And after years, if somebody went, well, you're sitting on my land.
Sorry, you didn't claim the knowledge.
I think actually that's what they did.
After so many years that nobody went to lay claim to them, they took over.
And this is what my father used to do.
This is his map that he actually made when he was going down into the mines in 1920.
Did you ever find out why he didn't move back to Mexico since he was doing so much of his work in Mexico?
Well, he was doing all right here.
I don't see why he would have to go over there.
Did he speak both English and Spanish?
Well, he used to read a lot of English, but he couldn't speak English.
But he could write it and understand Spanish and Latin.
Now, you learned to read and write in Spanish.
Where did you learn to read and write in Spanish?
Well, I went over there to Jesus and Mary Academy.
They taught more Spanish than you.
They did, more Spanish than me.
Well, this was a private school that you went to.
So you were actually educated in both languages.
How long did you go to school?
Yes, all my grades over there.
What did you do after you got out of school?
Well, I started working over here at the, what was it?
It was a little store in Norbury.
And then I got married, and then he wouldn't let me go to work.
Every year a kid, how could I go to work?
No, I like staying home with all my kids.
Now, we sort of cut off your story in the middle and changed over.
Okay, your father, when we stopped, your father had gone back to Mexico, and this was in 19... Is he 50?
Well, he went back to Mexico.
Actually, he went back to Mexico when I was 14 years old.
That would be back in, what would it be, 19...
Well, what year were you born?
Well, what year were you born?
Had he ever become an American citizen?
My mother did, because she always loved the United States.
I don't know why, but she was very happy here.
In fact, she said to Mexico, I'll never go.
She went to visit your aunt in Chihuahua.
She didn't visit Mexico, but that's all she did.
But to live, she never lived in Mexico.
Now, her family, her sisters and brothers stayed in Mexico.
In fact, they still live in Chihuahua.
She's got a brother and her sister.
They're pretty old now, a couple of ages.
And they raised their children in Mexico.
Actually, I haven't kept in touch with them.
I don't know, but I used to go on vacations.
Somehow, they always worked in bars, I think, or something like that.
They would travel around the country.
What they did, I don't know.
I don't think anybody... Well, Francisco, I think he worked for the government.
Yeah, he worked for the government.
In fact, he's sort of a sheriff or what do you call it?
A police official in some little town south of Chihuahua.
And he's, what kin is he to you?
He's your cousin on your mother's side.
And he's about the only one that has a steady job.
He's had a steady job here, I can remember.
But the other ones have a little store.
Oh, he was a bar owner of a restaurant.
Maybe I'd better draw them down, too.
Let's see, your mother's name was?
And she was from Zacatecas, Zacatecas.
And then how many brothers and sisters did she have?
Aurelio's a brother, and Rosa's her sister.
Oh, he's got about 12 kids, I think.
When they came to Chihuahua, they all stayed at Chihuahua.
Oh, all of your mother's family came to Chihuahua together?
Yeah, after the capture of Zacatecas, they left Zacatecas because it was...
Well, they were peaceful people and they didn't like, uh...
So they were, you know, the lot they were going through in Zacatecas.
And the way that my mother told me... You see, my grandmother's sister, my grandmother's sister was in Chihuahua.
And they were riding to each other.
And then my mother, my grandmother's sister...
sent for her, she says, why don't you come over and see if you like this thing, Chihuahua.
And you can bring the family if you like it.
Well, what was your grandmother's name?
And your grandfather's name on your mother's side was?
Do you know what he did in Zacatecas before he had to leave?
He was a blacksmith by trade.
He had a shop there, a blacksmith's shop.
He was doing very well, but like I say, they didn't like the way...
The life they were going through because of the soldiers and all that, you know, barring the girls and all that.
This is the blacksmith, the blacksmith Guadalupe.
And she was from a Zacatecas family too.
And then he was a blacksmith and doing very well in Zacatecas.
And oh, you said your mother was listed in the birth records as a mestiza.
So they were still listing people that way.
Yeah, they were listing people that way.
And so their children were already fairly well-grown.
In fact, my uncle, he was learning the trade.
Aurelio was learning to be a blacksmith.
In fact, I think that's the work he did all his life.
When he came to Chihuahua, he got a job with a railroad.
I was just reading about the taking of Zacatecas and apparently it was really terrible.
The way my mother tells me that the federal forces in Zacatecas had told the people that Dictate could never be captured.
And my mother tells me that about 10 o'clock in the morning
He's starting to hear the people at the IVN and IVN, and here they come, see.
And just the advance troops of Villa were starting to attack.
And my mother-in-law said, first it was just a cannon roar, then machine gun, and then in about an hour or so, he said, you can distinguish a bullet from a cannon, just like a...
a pot of boiling frijoles, you know, just a boiling kettle.
That's the way it did here, you know, and then pretty soon all the government forces were falling back.
They were being defeated, you know, and the VF forces were breaking through.

And she remembers that the poor federal soldiers were shedding their uniforms and asking the people for clothes, you know, because they knew that they were going to get killed, you know, and they got captured.
And so, he said it didn't take too long before the force of it was running through the streets, yelling and shooting and everything.
And it was just a terrible thing.
How old was she at that time?
I don't really know, but I think she was in her 20s.
Did she say what her family did?
Did they lock up their house or what?
Yeah, they stayed indoors for I don't know how many days.
And they didn't stay too long in Zacatecas when my grandmother's aunt wrote her and told her.
She couldn't stand it anymore, but come to Chihuahua and see how they liked it.
And they went to my grandmother's...
and stayed there for a while, and they found a home.
They found a place to live.
My aunt, she was younger, a lot younger than my mother.
I think she was, oh, about 10 or 15 years younger.
And she started working in a clothes factory, and then my mother started working at the
How had your aunt happened to go to Chihuahua in the first place?
I really don't know how she come to be in Chihuahua at that time.
But anyway, she was there, and your parents went and joined her.
And were your great-grandparents still alive at that time?
The only, on my great grandparent's side that I got to know because she was very old.
In other words, my grandmother, my grandmother's sister.
She was an aunt to my grandmother.
I remember the first time we went there in 1929, 1930, I saw her.
And where did you visit her?
Well, maybe your mother's family was from Chihuahua originally, before she married your father.
I'll tell you why, because my father, I remember he used to kill my mother, because the people from Zacatecas, they have a...
The way people speak, you know.
They can tell people from Zacatecas right away.
Once they hear him speak, you know.
And for years and years and years, even after she was living here, my mother would... Have you been to Mexico City?
Wonder, do you know, did you ever hear, was your father with Villa when Zacatecas was attacked?
That would be very interesting if he was.
That would have been very interesting.
Your father wasn't around always with him.
And Villa took many of his, he used most of his army.
And he was a very good friend of Villa.
Oh, he always had his picture.
I mean, well, I shouldn't have given it away, but I didn't care.
A friend of my father's, you know, when he learned that my father had died, he says, your father promised me a Pancho Villa's picture.
I said, okay, you can have it.
So I gave it to him.
But, you know, it was something I should have kept.
My mother, she always was afraid of bees, and she hated bees.
She always told me, you know, I guess she used to say, God punished me.
I always hated bees, and I had to marry one.
Now, I don't know the truth.
She never told me, but before I married my father, she was, I don't know, she was maybe in love with a telegraph operator, and he got killed by the police or something like that.
That's probably why she hated him.
Was that in Zacatecas or in Zacatecas?
He may have been killed during the battle.
And that would have been the Battle of Zacatecas, I believe, was in 1913.
So that's when they left and went to Chihuahua, where she had the sister who could help her.
And they began to work and do whatever they could, because she was working in a hospital.
And it was when she was working in a hospital that your father was brought in with a bullet in his leg.
And he was brought in from Celaya.
And that was probably the Battle of Celaya, which would have been in... No, I don't know what year it was at that time.
The Battle of Celaya was in 1915.
Would that be the right date?
Yeah, I have it here on the... My ta Rosa, she married a villista, too.
Yeah, and he was in the hospital, too.
And she had been working in the clothing factory, but she met this Villista.
What was his name, her husband's name?
He was a major in the Villas Army.
And he also got wounded in that Battle of Celaya.
They were both lucky to be alive at all, because I don't know how many thousands of Villistas were killed at Celaya.
I think, I'm not quite sure, but I think they were friends there.
And I think my father, I think he introduced Luis to my aunt.
And after they married, he didn't have to leave.
Did he have to leave Luis Gonzalez and Rosa?
They stayed in Chihuahua, that's right.
So they weren't in danger, or did they have to hide when the Villistas were being rounded up?
No, because, I mean, after he left Don Luis, I mean, he was at peace, in other words.
He probably, I don't think he let anybody know if he was a Villista or not.

but like my mother used to call the same mother it was all your fault you know just yeah yeah i'm very proud of my beast and all that oh we talk too much yeah yeah but you but his friend your your uncle uh or your man's husband luis gonzalez kept his mouth shut now what kind of work did he do after he became at peace
Well, I think he had a... Well, he started bars.
He had the two bars in Chihuahua.
Yeah, he was doing very well.
So he didn't have to leave.
They just left him alone because nobody remembered who he was.
And then he had... How many children did he have?
Are they the bunch that you were talking about that you think just stayed in the bar business?
And they still have, do they still have bars in Chihuahua?
I haven't kept in touch with them for, I don't know, for about the last 10 years.
In Francisco, did you put Pancho in?
Pancho is the one that he sent.
He's a big shot over there in Chihuahua.
He's a police officer down in some... Secret service or something like that.
He's not... Yeah, well, he's something, some kind of an official, I don't know.
Okay, I have Armando, Luis, Enrique, Marta, Francisco.
He's got a bunch of kids.
He's even a grandfather by now, I think.
Yeah, that's the way it goes.
Do you know where Luis Gonzalez was from originally?
Harilio, who was a blacksmith, had 12 kids, and they're all in Chihuahua, too.
And you don't know what they do?
No, the boys, I don't know what they do.
You went to see them last time, about...
The last time I went was at Chihuahua's room on Friday night.
Oh, that was about 10 years ago, when he died in Chihuahua.
But your aunt has... Well, she's been here.
Have you ever thought about moving back to Mexico?
What is your impression of Mexico?
How do you feel about it?
No, it's all right, I guess, for some people.
Staying over there, our kids are used to here in El Paso.
Now, if they want to, they can travel.
You know, my kids, every time we put a horse in a car or something like that, as soon as we call the cops, I mean, now we're breathing fresh air.
Because they have that impression, Juarez, it's something like Mexico.
They haven't been to Mexico City.
Mexico City is not like this at all.
Every place you go, it's different.
When did you go down there?
No, I keep going down there.
About two years ago, was I in Mexico City with Teresa?
My daughter, Teresa, she got on vacation in Mexico City.
In fact, we want him to go see Bertha now.
I've been going every year now.
Every time that she has the babies, I've been going over there with Bertha.
Now, I didn't find out, oh, that's what I wanted to know.
What did your mother do after your father left and went back to Mexico?
How did she make a living for your brothers and sisters?
Well, she had a hard time, very hard time.
She worked most of her life working the laundries.
And how many brothers and sisters did you have?
That's why I had to leave school.
My first year of high school.
And then what did you do?
At that time, they had this Civilian Conservation Corps, the CCCs.
I stayed there for three years.
left and worked there at Beaumont Hospital for another three years.
Then I went to the service, came out of the service, went to work for Southern Pacific.
Worked there for about six months and then I got my job at Munson and I've been there since then.
Well, I work at a department.
I'm sort of a sporting goods clerk, you know.
Take care of the sporting department there in Clemson.
And did you, when you were a child, did your family speak Spanish or did they?
They always did speak Spanish and that's how I learned Spanish.
I learned to read and write just by
You went to school here in El Paso.
And your brother, your living brother, what... Well, he was, after he left school, it was during the war, he went to the Navy, got out of the Navy, and then came out of the Navy, got married,
Lived for a few years and he died.
And did he have any children?
One they named Rodolfo and the other one Roberto.
We haven't heard from them for a long, long time.
I think they're in school, college or something.
So your brother went on up to Dallas.
Then on your father's side of the family, he had brothers and sisters too.
He was the black sheep, I think.
Let's see, the youngest was Wenceslado.
And my Tia Rosa and my father.
And where did, now your father's parents were from, I know I've got this on tape, but I've forgotten right now.
But you know, what was her name?
No, not on my father's side.
And where does, is he still living?
And where did he live, though, didn't he?
He always stayed in Juarez, he did.
In fact, all of my brothers and sisters stayed in New Mexico.
And his children, are they in Juarez, Manuel's children?
I don't know, five, let's see.
I had one cousin that came to the United States, and they never heard of him again.
And all the other state in Mexico.
I think he came to the United States for several years because he learned to speak English.
And his job in Juarez was the city guide or something like that.
He used to make a living out of taking people.
Yeah, he was a city guide or something like that.
Concepcion, Paula, Refugio, and that's it?
And I think Paula and, are they here in El Paso?
Yeah, Paula, do you know El Paso?

I don't remember now, I don't know for sure, but I think my two men made it, and my two ones, they came to the United States and lived in Colorado and California, some of them, for several years, and then they went back to Mexico.
When did they come to the United States?
I know that Antonio, my cousin, died last year or two years ago.
He was older than you, wasn't he?
Do you remember why they came?
Did they come because of the revolution or they just came for work?
I think they were just looking for work.
Whatever happened to your grandfather's lands at Valladolid?
My father told me one time that they left them to one of the relatives and they never claimed them back or anything like that.
They just, you know, moved out and never went back again.
And this was in the 1920s and then they eventually settled down in Juarez.
He died here in El Paso, my grandfather.
He died here in El Paso.
I don't know if I'll ever be keeping this.
Now, let's see what happened to your children.
That was my grandmother that my father sent.
Was she also from Valle de Allende?

In fact, the sad part of this, the thing that they tell me, well, my father never admitted it, but my grandmother died of a heart attack because she was, when my father got wounded, he got pretty sick, she got a heart attack and she never recovered, or she recovered in any way, he never saw her again.
while he was in the hospital, see?
And he used to tell me that, I guess my father didn't care to ask about his mother, and I really don't know because one time he told me that he was out with some friends of his, you know, cronies,
And one of them said, well, what are you talking about?
You don't even have a mother.
What do you mean I don't have a mother?
Well, why don't you ask your father?
She's been dead for a year now.
He didn't even know about it.
And then he told me my father went over to my grandfather's house and got him up in the middle of the night.
And my grandfather, he said, well, yeah, I'll wake him tomorrow morning.
I'll show you the grave and all that.
No, you show it to me right now.
Try to get him out of the house.
And they tell me that my father got the gun out.
He said, you show it to me right now or I'm going to kill you.
Your grandfather was in Chihuahua by that time.
My grandfather had to get up in the middle of the night, take him over to the cemetery, and show him where his mother was buried.
And this was before he left for El Paso, before he had to leave for El Paso.
And how had your grandfather and grandmother happened to come to Chihuahua from Valle de Allende?
I think that, I don't remember.
But I just assumed that they had been following my father.
I was wondering if maybe there was trouble with the revolutionary soldiers in the area where they were trying to farm.
The people always come into the because of the soldiers that caused the revolution because they were tearing up the place apart.
So it's down to the south, to the southeast.
Did anything happen, do you ever hear about the Battle of Parral?
No, I never heard of that, the Battle of Parral, but that's where the...
They used to mention Parral and Santa Rosalia, which they call it Camargo now, but my father always called it Santa Rosalia.
I think they even had relatives there, I'm pretty sure, because on my father's side, it was a minus.
The governor reminded us, remember he had a brother, and his brother, or my father, he always called him cousin.
Whether it were cousins or not, I don't know.
But I know that we do have relatives with the last name Mike.
Even here, they came to El Paso, or somewhere in El Paso, I don't know where.
But they had relatives all over the Parrales, Santa Rosalina.
Do you know when that family came north to take up land there?
May have been in the 1700s, perhaps.
And then spread out, and that's why there would be all those cousins all over.
Now, what I didn't find out about was your children.
Let's see, which one is your oldest?
He's going to, he said, last year of college.
Where is he going to college?
And then he lives at home.
Oh, no, he just moved out.
He and another son of ours.
He wants to be a lawyer.
And then your next child is?
I don't know what's his... Are they still living at home?
She goes to Osprey High School.
Goes to Osprey his first year.
He's one year older than my daughter.
Cecilia, she goes to school, grade school.
And then I have three miscarriages, so that's 12.
And you go back to Mexico every so often?
Or you go to Mexico every so often?
Well, I have my relatives over there in Mexico.
So do I, but I don't know.
But you like to travel, and I do, I do like to travel.
So once in a while, I go.
Every year, every two years, we go to Mexico.
But you say your children don't like it?
But have they ever been, any of your children, south of Chihuahua?
